PMID== 9830491
TI  == [microwave effect on survival of sporulated bacteria inoculated in minced meat].
AB  == due to the current tendency of cooking and heating meat prepared foods in microwave ovens and the possibility that they transmit bacterial diseases, the survival rate of spore-forming bacteria was evaluated in minced meat samples. meat was innoculated with a known number of bacillus cereus and clostridium perfringens spores, and laterly thawed and cooked in an amana microwave oven (2450 hz). survival rate was determined according to the methodology described by vanderzant & splittstoesser, and the activity of the enzyme acid phosphatase was  determined as cooking parameter. b. cereus spore showed a decrease in its number  as the time of exposition increased, but without fully disappearing. c. perfringens spores also decreased in number, but showed a later increase, associated with the germination of survival spores.
